The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech suppliers offer practically all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces classical at lower prices.
Maybe this one won't wait for a long time.
The fact that the Czech mobile providers are one of the most expensive in Europe at all, we have often reported on Mobil.cz.
This also confirmed the telecommunications authority ČTÚ, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher here than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the area of roaming fees regulation, a paradoxical situation is likely - for some customers from Czech mobile phone providers, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a fight announcement.
Perhaps it sounds paradox, in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
The mobile providers, on the other hand, like to shun the fact that there is extremely much competition in the Czech market.
The Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who had often said in the past that there was no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a classic provider with its own network has no extraordinarily many chances (likely, it would not even find frequencies).
But there is another way - a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers to the mobile market brought a significant price reduction, which the classic mobile providers had to react.
Before entering such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, there were similar votes on the UK market as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you don't have to look for examples long.
In February we reported about the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus ascend to the five largest supplier of the country.
The financial group Penta, which has U:fon in the Czech Republic, is behind mobilisation.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to work effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need relatively high costs for the construction, operation and entertainment of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers are usually elected as low-cost companies - they offer cheap phone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive service offer.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobilizing in Poland shows, it can also be a very good chess to put on a non-clinical target group.
This provider is specifically addressed to men.
"Real guys choose mobiles - the provider that they like and who they can trust," said David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator company of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a concept similar to that in Poland could take foot in the Czech Republic.
The press speaker of Vodafone Miroslav Čepický also doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively satisfactory from the point of view of the service offer."
In the Czech Republic, the mobile phone providers think
But it is almost sure that if a virtual mobile provider conquers Czech Republic, this will not be mobilizing.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not particularly hopeful.
It will rather be a market entry of mobilking in other countries of our region," says a telephone call for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, press speaker of the Penta financial group.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile service providers in the Czech Republic are not particularly generous to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do all they can to make no potential competitor.
Their interest in launching a virtual mobile service provider has been showing the Group GTS Novera for a long time, which wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of company customers.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed network, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the earlier, the better.
About this possibility we have negotiated repeatedly with all Czech mobile providers.
With some of them we have already been able to achieve negotiation progress," says the press speaker of the Pavel Kaidl group.
Maybe better times are coming now.
Not official information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
" At this moment we do not assume that there is room for a full-quality virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has large specificities compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has addressed us with a complex and serious project in this area," says Vlastimil Sršeň in his statement on Mobil.cz Vlastimil from the Press Department of Telefónica O2.
Other suppliers also point to the specific nature of the Czech market.
The press speaker of T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds in rare terms to O2's statement: "We have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project on which we could continue to build."
And she adds: "A virtual provider will hardly appear in the T-Mobile network until the end of the year.
At this moment we should already have a specific offer to be able to think so shortly."
Vodafone focuses more on fulfilling the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says: "We are open for negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of cost and infrastructure.
This is exactly what we consider best from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is looking for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile Internet."
The responsible authorities - with the providers hand in hand
The approach of the mobile providers is easy to understand, another provider called more competition, this would reduce prices and thus lead to a decrease in profits.
So why should such a competitor be made easier to enter the market?
That, when it comes to something, the providers can move on a stake, the long way back and forth also demonstrates the origin of U:fon.
The most likely pressure towards ČTÚ came from society T-Mobile when U:fon came to the market.
This also demonstrates the publicly accessible information from the ČTÚ websites.
But now, U:fon is suitable as an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competition in the mobile market has recently also been strengthened by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile telephone provider.
Taking into account the character of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is evident that a new player would put high requirements on the market itself and above all its services."
However, in view of this approach the mobile provider is surprised by the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities.
This is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ, which, unfortunately, in Czech, is not the competence of the United Kingdom and other highly developed states to intervene in economic competition.
It has exclusively the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
However, this was a very typical attitude to this whole problem.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile provider and a virtual provider through the renting of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, because the offer of potential stakeholders was probably not sufficiently interesting for classical providers," said Kristián Chalupa, in his answer to our request from the Department of Foreign Relations of the ÚOHS.
Such a formulation would not be surprised by representatives of the providers.
This is more than worrying from an authority representing consumer interests and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses its position on the market.
In particular, if Kristián Chalupa adds: "In the abroad where virtual providers work very normal, it is observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile phone services."
However, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not among the interests of the ÚOHS.
Really shocking is the almost already touching agreement of the three mobile providers, resulting from their reactions.
The question whether it really is just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same petrol price at the tank stations is certainly just a coincidence and the result of a hard competition.
"The Authority has not discovered any signs of action against competition in this matter, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
No one of the suppliers has a dominant market position, so he does not have the corresponding increased responsibility for his market action.
The necessary instruments for opening the mobile market for virtual providers are probably also missing by the regulatory authority for telecommunications," said Chalupa in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, developed by the ČTÚ, after which telecommunications from the point of view of economic competition is a single market.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile providers have a dominant position.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different viewpoint - for the entry into the market of a virtual provider, the approval of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile provider - logically - has the monopoly for its network.
This means that he necessarily takes a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if you are not involved in this argument, it should be at least a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile network providers are acting dramatically similar.
In this context, complaints of a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera) demonstrate that they are very similar obstacles in negotiations with all providers.
The deviation of responsibility to the ČTÚ is then a rather common trick in the telecommunications services with which the ÚOHS dismisses from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the new telecommunications law, recently adopted, has failed to enforce the expansion of the ČTÚ competences in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must only know all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's okay if no one looks at it.
The functioning of any pseudo-virtual provider, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks, remains unobserved.
It is companies who spend their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but which are only partially public.
Usually, it is companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
Own mobile phone services offer, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only come to the chosen ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company appears to the operator as a classic company expertise, which orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he will then receive special prize offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit similar sales.
"If there are cases that you describe, it may be a violation of the contractual conditions with which we will then deal with, which can lead to an end to cooperation with the corresponding society," Martina Kemrová answered on our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing does not happen with the controllers of the mobile phone providers.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such action.
The activities of these companies do not lead to neglecting profits, while they are not affected by the actual official marketing, in contrast to the actual virtual providers.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite all, the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card does not run on their name in their phone, so they cannot have full value over it as the normal customers of the mobile phone providers."
This alone, however, would at least have to happen to the ČTÚ.
A further question for the ÚOHS is also open.
The mobile providers close their eyes before such a procedure, why are they locking themselves against a virtual provider?
It is added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competences to identify such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the declaration of providers, they do not know of it and their terms and conditions would forbid it.
When the Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been stressed several times in the text, the market entry of virtual providers brought a significant price reduction in the various services.
In this context, practically in all countries where virtual providers have developed, classical providers are trying to prevent their origin practically more or less.
The arguments used by them were practically identical - a market too small, or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, these moments were just incorporated by the regulatory bodies, which were not trying to preserve the interests of the mobile providers but those of their customers.
Be it by formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and further followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing up the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experiences, we cannot discern the impression that ignorance in the competences in these cases is more than beneficial.
But we don't throw the flinth into the grain.
When the background information is accorded and soon a virtual provider appears, the Czech mobile market may move again soon.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive when it comes to rejecting other stakeholders (discriminating).
And the Czechs will finally not call more expensive than the rest of Europe.
