Discussion - From Blood that was safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated yesterday the 10th anniversary of its founding, and her president, Dr. Francine Décary, had all reason to rejoice because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And, above all, it recovered the confidence of the public, which was severely shocked by the scandal of polluted blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As you know, the national blood reserves managed by the blood donation service of the Canadian Red Cross were contaminated with the HI virus and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Given this drama and the public's dissatisfaction, the Government of Canada initiated in February 1994 a public investigation led by the judge Horace Krever aimed at bringing light to the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy, and drafting directives to prevent another catastrophe of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still hesitating to submit his report, several provinces at the time placed a committee on the legs whose goal was to develop a new system for the management of blood conservations in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this commission.
According to the reports by Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were founded in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian blood society to provide the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec started her work, hardly 38% of people had confidence in the blood conservation system in Quebec, Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood conservations and through the work in this area during the following years, we have recovered the public's confidence before proudly stressing that at the beginning of 2008 almost 94% of Quebec's population had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in mind that `confidence is something extremely fragile'.
Hema-Quebec has been acting in accordance with the principle of caution since its founding on 28 September 1998.
At this time, we experienced the occurrence of many cases of the human form of bovine madness in Europe, a new type of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells this woman who has been the leadership since the founding of 1998.
`And we didn't have the least idea whether this disease could be transmitted over blood.
So we call on one of the main directives of the reports by Krever and Gélineau, which suggests that we apply exclusion measures, if we do not know this and if a disease progresses only slowly, as is obviously the case in the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is expressed by a degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, there was no acceptance of blood from people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than one month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago, without any doubt it was proved that this disease was transmitted over the blood.
This event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied has quite a sense.
In 1999, a much more precise technique for detecting HIV was published on the market: The nucleic acid tests (NST) allowing the occurrence of the virus itself directly in the blood of the donor, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the previously used tests.
The NST allowed it to shorten the incubation time that takes place between the time when the person was infected and when the first viruses can be proved by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than one week.
Thus, the risk that certain donors could be infected without knowing it and you could not recognize this has been significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Today, one of 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
`In other words, this means that you should distribute 12 million blood conservations before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec is distributed between 400,000 and 500,000 blood conservations each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case occurs where HIV was transmitted via a blood conservation.
I think that today you can feel comfortable when you get or write a blood transfusion to restore health," says the director of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogens can get into the system.
Only last year on the island of Réunion has the Chikungunya virus appeared, which, just like the Westnil virus, is transmitted by insects over the blood.
We have to monitor continuously," continues Dr. Décary before she stresses that Hema-Quebec must also provide adequate supply next to a safe supply.
`Demand increases because the population ages.
Since cancer control treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or blood plates.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor network, which is an average of only 3% of Quebec's blood donations.
Every healthy person who is 18 years or older and who meets the criteria for fitness can spend blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of those who provide their blood are not accepted because they are, for example, AIDS or malaria, and whoever has traveled to a country where malaria is spread is excluded from blood donation for a year.
`With these 3% we manage to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Lack of stocks are very rare.
But you need to renew the members of this donor network if they are older and can no longer donate blood.
It is difficult to convince people of donating blood, but above all to keep them and bring them to become regular donors.
Life is so witty today that you rarely find the time to spend an hour of blood donation," regrets Francine Decary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec delivers not only blood conservations but also human tissues, including bone transplants, cardiovascular valves, augap and skin, which is almost exclusively used in severe burning.
These tissues are investigated, processed and frozen before they are stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public navel cord of Quebec.
In the needle cord, which was previously considered biomedical waste, there is rich blood on stem cells that can be used to treat severe diseases, such as leukaemia.
`A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our thousandth navel snorkel blood sample, and we plan to decrease more than a thousand per year.
`We should begin to make it available for transplants at the beginning of next year', continues Dr. Décary, who describes this program of navel cord reduction as very popular.
`Many mothers are convinced not to have access to it' because Hema-Quebec lacks the means to offer this complex and costly program in all Quebec hospitals.
