It is mostly affected by historical places full of memories, "it is like a friend to lose with which one has laid a piece of street full of emotions," says the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso", who brought him the Oskar and the great price of Cannes. It is the history of a pre-city kinus and its nostalgic, which consists of living in a probably forever lost cinema world.
The figures that the Anec, the central commercial association, delivers speak a clear language: in the last five years, the vast amount of 316 traditional cinemas has had to be closed; most of these have paid the cinemas in the large cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
One of the most affected regions is the Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This proves that the main guilty are the multiplexkinos, because they are just these three regions where the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: at 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy has the lists, 81 are both in Tuscany and in the Emilia Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," said Paolo Protti, the president of the Anec, "it is useful that new structures also arise, but the preservation of the already existing, because a hall in the city closes, not all its clients are ready to visit a multiplexkino in the periphery instead of the old.
And here remains the missing budget for the Fond of the Commercial Association: the debt burden recorded by the State amounts to about 10 million euros.
It is a shame of the ethical and moral view that the government does not observe existing laws.
In order to preserve the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros would be in the year of need."
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city, which, due to the fears of the old cinema halls, decided to protect them by an agreement between the municipality and the Anec; it is the first agreement of this kind in Italy that aims to protect and support the traditional cinemas, both in the historical center and in the periphery.
Among the planned measures are tax advances for the cinema drivers as well as benefits for the public in terms of public transport: it will be allowed to go into the transport restricted areas of the centre and also to park more favourable parking fees.
"It is a delightful initiative," says Giuseppe Tornatore, "I hope that other cities will join our example and also develop new concepts.
But surely we also need a better audio and video equipment to be able to align something against the superpower of the multiplex halls, because the audience of today is more demanding.
The defense of the traditional cinema has always been an important theme for me: the closure of the "Supercinema" of Baghiera, the place of my childhood and youth, was the crucial point that led me to set up the "Nuovo cinema paradiso" even though I had played with the thought for ten years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years; when I pass the Rialto or the Quirinale in the Via Nazionale, where I have experienced so many different emotions, I turn to the side to avoid seeing the dust-covered posters.
