When the energy escapes from the waves, the greats suddenly run up
It is an unchanging source of money, which covers over 70% of the planet's surface and seems to understand only now the world's major energy companies.
Wells, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that all look at now, and also seek to occupy, such as giants like Chevron.
The possibility of gaining energy from the sea movements has been considered and examined for 70 years; these studies have not accidentally intensified significantly since the first oil crisis.
As the price of oil broke in around 1980, the idea of marine energy is gasped, but now the environmental organizations and the increased oil price are pushing for new impulses in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the global energy needs could be covered by the energy generated by the ocean waves.
This would be equal to the double of the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, the currents and tides were also coming.
Giants in attack.
The first company that now sets on marine energy is Enersis, who signed a contract for the establishment of a power plant in northern Portugal in 2005.
When this message was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, there are now more and more companies from the traditional energy industry, which focus on marine energy production.
"Chevron investigates these technologies" – the speaker of a company known to the US giant in the Wall Street Journal – and considers the possibility to cooperate with us."
This concerns the acquisition of an authorisation by the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to launch a project before the coast of Alaska.
This is a not to be underestimated sign, e.g. when one considers that oil is continued by the US in Alaska and President Bush has recently launched the plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey are also investing in the new industry; the details are not known, but observers speak of an increasing interest.
Enhanced technologies.
Experts speak of a technology still in the burst, which is not last because the last doubts of the environmental protectionists have not yet been clarified.
To date, projects such as those in Portugal and also Scotland are of a rather small dimension and do not seem to cause any serious environmental problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with far greater impact on the environment need to be produced.
There are different possibilities: Ocean Power uses a system of connected bows.
The swim of the waves, which moves the bows up and down, is transformed into hydraulic pressure through pistons and cylinders within the swimmer.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The current is then sent via underwater lines to the coast.
To date, there are four planned installations of this type, which are only waiting for state approval. Some of the energy gained could also serve for military institutions.
Verdant Power, however, already produces energy for a warehouse and a parklat with the help of underseas turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feed the generator by the resulting rotating movement.
According to Verdant, a long snake of possible clients already awaits the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute of Electricity Profiting Research, a particular interest deserves at present the potential that lies in the tides.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, tides are better predictable than wind currents, sun radiation and waves, and therefore a more reliable source of power.
Especially the tidal energy that states such as New York, Maine and Alaska and other coastal states have already invested 7.5 million dollars in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
